postcontent:
Marble Knife – This the Ideal Model with a red, curley Maple handle, brass hilt and alum. pommel.  The blade is about 5 7/8 in long and has slight corrosion at the tip.  Marble made many hunting knives up until just before WWII when they started to make fighting knives for the Armed Forces.
Remington and Kabar also got into this business and Marbles finally dropped out but they are the ones who originally designed knives with a fullers groove, aka “blood groove”.  They made an abundance of these blades before they went out of business and stored them.  When the company was re-started  recently they incorporated the stock of old blades in the newer knives. title: For Sale:  TOZ 35M Free Pistol
postcontent:
For the first time in literally years TOZ 35s are on the market again! These are Soviet pistols designed for Olympic competition. They are in fantastic shape, most likely never fired outside the factory. They still have original uncut grips serialized to the gun (expect to spend a long time with a Dremel or get a help from someone who knows how to make free style grips). The pistol comes with what appears to be full kit (although I do not guarantee completeness to factory spec here - some small parts may be missing!).

Take a look at the list of world championship wins delivered by this gun here: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_pistol.

This is an FFL transaction - NICS check will be performed. Taxes are extra.

FAQ

Q. How do I buy?
A. This is a dealer listing, NICS check, taxes, etc are all required. Please go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick up.

Q. I am interested in your gun. Is it still available?
A. If you see this ad, most likely. The firearms are reserved for pickup on my web site, by making an appointment to buy. Someone could be doing it right now, and first person to reserve the firearm wins. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment on the site. If someone has made it just before you, I will notify you within a short time (usually, an hour), otherwise - see you shortly.

PLEASE DO NOT ASK WHETHER THE GUN IS STILL AVAILABLE! I WILL NOT RESPOND.

Q. I am interested in your gun. Call me @ xxx-xxx-xxxx
A. Excellent. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick it up.

Q. Are there any other fees, in addition to the price and taxes? NICS, background check, etc?
A. No.

Q. What is the tax rate?
A. 9.5%

Q. Where are you located?
A. Queen Anne neighborhood in Seattle.

Q. Can we meet in Burien on Monday morning?
A. No, FFL requirements are that the transfers happen at a licensed location. Also, the only times you can come over are the appointments that you can reserve on the site. No other time slots are available.

Q. I see you carry Savage rifles. Can you find me MKII FV-SR?
A. No. Please see here for what I can or cannot do: http://www.preciseshooter.com/NotInStock.aspx

Q. Do you take trades?
A. Sometimes. However:
a) firearms only,
b) they need to be our of current production (I can get new ones at wholesale prices), or you have to offer them to me at well below wholesale
c) I do not resell the trades, so they should fit my personal interests (which only include military as well as highly accurate, competition guns - no self defense guns like Glocks, M&Ps, XD*, and the like)
d) the exchange rate should be fair (see here for more: http://www.preciseshooter.com/blog/PriceGuide.aspx

Q. Is the price firm? Will you take XXX (70% of the asking price)?
A. The price is firm.

Q. Will you ship?
A. I prefer to not ship this gun, but I have made exceptions in the past. If you REALLY want it shipped, please understand that I have not fired it, so I don't know if it works, and that if it doesn't, you will have to work with CAI to repair or replace it. Also, shipping is expensive - $40 via insured Priority Mail. It is a very big and heavy box.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Chiappa Rhino 50DS (5 inch barrel)
postcontent:
I'm selling/trading my Chiappa Rhino 50DS in .357 magnum. Still has original box, manual, and brush. It's only had about 200 rounds put through it and still runs like it did when it was new. Has a rail under the barrel so you can attach your favorite flashlight or laser.

If you don't know about the Rhinos, they have their barrels aligned with the lowest cylinder, so the recoil from each shot goes straight back into your wrist and reduces muzzle rise. A rhino will have much less felt recoil and muzzle rise than a conventional magnum revolver. .38 specials out of the Rhino feel like .22lr's and you can go through a box of .357 mag without having sore wrists afterwards. Designed by the same man who designed the Mateba Autorevolver, the Rhino shares a lot of the same characteristics, mainly the lower axis barrel. 

I'm in no real hurry to sell this pistol, I just don't have the time to shoot it anymore and would prefer to have a semiautomatic pistol for home defense. 

I'd prefer to trade this for a HK 45, HK USP (or compact), or a double stack 1911, Sig Sauer 1911, a glock 34 with some cash, ammo, or accessories on your end, but will also take $850 cash for it. Contact me via email with offers, worse I can say is no and will respond to all offers.

title: For Sale:  Sporterized Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
I sporterized this Mosin Nagant (started as a 91/30) last year for deer season for my buddy.  He took a decent buck with it using Brown Bear 203 grain ammo.

The barrel has been cut to 17.5" and recrowned.  The bolt was bent by cutting and rewelding it.  The stock was cut down some at the front and refinished.  The buttstock has a recoil pad fitted (although not perfectly), but the original metal buttplate can be included and can easily be reinstalled.  There are no iron sights on this rifle, but it has a Picatinny rail installed in place of the rear sight base.  (The rear sight base on a Mosin sits on a 3/8" dovetail.  This rail adapter goes from 3/8" dovetail to Picatinny, and has a set screw to stop it from moving under recoil.)

The only think you need to set this gun up for a deer season is to add a "scout" style long eye relief scope.  We used a cheap NcStar 2-7x pistol scope, which worked great.

Selling some guns to raise funds for another project, so snatch this Mosin up cheaper than they can be had from Bud's with sporterizing work already done to it.

title: For Sale:  FN 1900
postcontent:
This is a cool old pistol that has been refinished.  The FN 1900 was one of John Moses Browning's first pistol designs, before he went on to create the Browning High Power and the 1911.  Browning couldn't find a US company that was interested in this design, so he sold it to the Belgian firm of FN Herstal.

This pistol was pretty worn out when I got it, so it has been refinished with a modern twist.  The entire pistol was Duracoated black, but the controls are all Duracoated "German red."

What makes this pistol unique is that it has a recoil spring and guide rod located ABOVE the barrel.  The barrel sits below the guide rod, and the right side of the frame has an ejection port.  Chambered in .32 ACP, this gun doesn't recoil much and is a pleasure to shoot.  When the magazine is empty, an indicator pops up in front of the rear sight to let the shooter know.  The grips are original, and are black, but they appear almost brownish in the pictures because of the flash.  Not a "collector's item" per se because of the refinishing (although it could be stripped and reblued if you wanted), but a very nice shooting example of a reliable old firearm.

The safety must be on "feu" to fire, and if the safety is on, the slide is locked and cannot be moved.

Includes one magazine, a few rounds of hollow points and a Blackhawk brand belt holster.
